  ],
  "final_text": "I'll pull the fault registers and NVIC state in parallel \u2014 SCB gives us the fault-status bits, NVIC tells us whether a pending/active interrupt is involved, and `fault-decode` gives a synthesised read.\nCorrect subcommand is `decode-hardfault`. Retrying all three in parallel:\nInteresting \u2014 all fault registers are zero. Let me pull the callstack and core registers to complete the picture before concluding:\nNow I have a complete picture. Here is the full classification:\n\n---\n\n## Crash Classification: Neither \u2014 This Is a Reset-Loop Entry Point\n\n**Verdict: The MCU was reset (likely by a watchdog or a software `NVIC_SystemReset()` call in a fault handler). You're looking at the very beginning of the *next* boot cycle, not the live crash state. The fault-register evidence is gone.**\n\n### Evidence, line by line\n\n| Signal | Value | What it means |\n|---|---|---|\n| `CFSR` | `0x00000000` | No MemManage, BusFault, or UsageFault was latched |\n| `HFSR` | `0x00000000` | No HardFault was latched |\n| `SHCSR` | `0x00000000` | No fault handler is active/pending |\n| `NVIC_ISERx` (all) | `0x00000000` | Zero IRQs enabled \u2014 HAL_Init hasn't run yet |\n| `VECTACTIVE` | `0` / Thread mode | CPU is in Thread mode, no exception active |\n| `PC` | `0x08001474` \u2192 `Reset_Handler:62` | Still inside startup assembly, before `main()` |\n| `LR` | `0xFFFFFFFF` | Reset default \u2014 no call has been made or returned |\n| `r0\u2013r12` | all `0x00000000` | Hardware-reset state; no application code has touched them |\n| `PSP` | `0x00000000` | Not initialised yet \u2014 startup hasn't set up the process stack |\n| `CONTROL` | `0x0` | MSP in use, privileged Thread mode \u2014 early startup |\n\n**This is not a frozen crash state; this is a pristine reset state.** The registers are exactly what you see immediately after the reset vector fires and before a single application instruction writes any GPR.\n\n### Why the fault registers are empty\n\nOn a system reset (triggered by IWDG, WWDG, or `NVIC_SystemReset()`), the SCB fault registers \u2014 CFSR, HFSR, MMFAR, BFAR \u2014 are all **cleared to zero by hardware**. Whatever faulted in the previous run is gone.\n\n---\n\n### What to do next \u2014 find the reset cause that survived\n\nThe `RCC_CSR` reset-cause flags **do survive** a system reset (they're sticky until software writes `RMVF`). Read them now:\nThe full dump is in the saved file. Let me extract just the `CSR` register with its reset-cause flags:\nThe reset-cause flags seal the diagnosis. Here is the final report:\n\n---\n\n## Final Classification: **Software-Reset From a Fault Handler** (not a pure interrupt problem, not silent memory corruption)\n\n### The definitive evidence \u2014 `RCC_CSR` reset-cause flags\n\n| Flag | Value | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| `SFTRSTF` | **1** | \u2705 **Software reset** \u2014 `NVIC_SystemReset()` was called |\n| `IWDGRSTF` | 0 | Independent watchdog did **not** fire |\n| `WWDGRSTF` | 0 | Window watchdog did **not** fire |\n| `BORRSTF` | 1 | Brown-out (sticky from initial power-on, not the proximate cause) |\n| `PINRSTF` | 1 | Pin reset (sticky from debug-connect or earlier reset) |\n\n`SFTRSTF=1` with the watchdog flags clear is the canonical signature of a fault handler that calls `NVIC_SystemReset()` to reboot rather than hang. Something in the previous run faulted, the HardFault (or MemManage/BusFault escalated to HardFault) handler ran, called `NVIC_SystemReset()`, and the reset cleared the SCB fault registers before you could read them. You caught the MCU at the very top of `Reset_Handler` on the next boot cycle.\n\n### Why it's not an interrupt problem\n\n- All `NVIC_ISERx = 0` \u2014 no IRQs were enabled at halt (startup hasn't run yet)\n- `ICSR.VECTACTIVE = 0` \u2014 Thread mode, no exception is active\n- `ICSR.ISRPENDING = 0` \u2014 no interrupt is pending\n- No CFSR stacking-error bits (`STKERR`, `UNSTKERR`, `MSTKERR`) that would indicate an IRQ-entry or IRQ-exit fault\n\n### Why it's not conclusively memory corruption either \u2014 but remains the prime suspect\n\nThe SCB registers were wiped by the software reset, so you cannot read the original CFSR bits. However `SFTRSTF` + `NVIC_SystemReset()` in a fault handler is by far the most common pattern when the root cause is an invalid-pointer dereference, stack overflow, or unaligned access \u2014 all forms of memory corruption. A pure interrupt misconfiguration (wrong vector, bad priority) would typically hang in the fault handler or spin, not cleanly call `NVIC_SystemReset()`.\n\n### Recommended next steps to catch it live\n\n1. **Instrument the fault handler before it resets** \u2014 add a software breakpoint (`__BKPT(0)`) or preserve a crash record in a `.noinit` RAM section before calling `NVIC_SystemReset()`. That lets you read CFSR/HFSR/stacked-PC on the *next* attach.\n\n2. **Enable halt-on-fault via DBGMCU** \u2014 write `DBGMCU_APB1FZR1` / `DBGMCU_CR` to freeze on HardFault so the debugger catches the fault in-place instead of letting the handler run:\n   ```\n   stm32 debug read-peripheral DBGMCU\n   ```\n\n3. **Re-flash and let it crash again with a breakpoint in `HardFault_Handler`** \u2014 once halted there, read the stacked frame (SP+0\u2026SP+28 = r0, r1, r2, r3, r12, LR, PC, xPSR) to recover the faulting PC and CFSR from the *live* run.\n\n**Bottom line: software reset from a fault handler, root cause almost certainly a processor fault (memory corruption is the leading candidate), but the reset scrubbed the forensics. The bug is in application code \u2014 catch it before the reset fires.**"
}